        description: "The Paris — Compiègne route takes you to a city rich in imperial history. Compiègne Palace, favourite residence of Napoleon III and Empress Eugénie, now houses three museums. The Forest of Compiègne, one of France's largest at 14,500 hectares, offers an exceptional natural setting.",
        routeDescription: "The route takes the A1 motorway towards Lille to the Compiègne-Sud exit. The journey is direct and fast, crossing northern Île-de-France and Picardy.",
        introduction: "Compiègne is the quintessential imperial city, marked by the stays of kings and emperors since the Middle Ages. The Imperial Palace of Compiègne, France's third largest after Versailles and Fontainebleau, was Napoleon III's favourite residence where he organised the 'Séries', sumptuous parties gathering Europe's elite throughout autumn. The palace now houses the Museum of the Second Empire, unique in France, the Empress Museum and the remarkable National Museum of the Car. The 14,500-hectare national forest of Compiègne, with its centuries-old beeches and oaks, is France's third largest. It is crisscrossed by hiking trails, bridleways and forest roads making it a paradise for nature lovers. The Armistice of 11 November 1918 was signed there in the Rethondes clearing, where a memorial and replica of the Armistice wagon perpetuate the memory. Compiègne combines ideally with a visit to Pierrefonds castle, just 14 km away, forming a complete imperial excursion from Paris.",
